# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-consciousness
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-consciousness/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-consciousness/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] It is divided into six sections: the first three cover existing work from philosophical, neurological and Darwinian perspectives.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Part IV presents the novel thesis of the work: the Dynamic Core Hypothesis.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] The remaining two parts explore how it resolves various philosophical and practical issues.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Since Descartes, philosophers have been occupied with the concept of consciousness and its subjective nature has posed a special problem for science.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Its nature arises from the neuronal structures in the brain and some understanding of these, together with the experimental tools needed to explore them, is given in the following chapters.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] They then recapitulate Edelman's still controversial theory of somatic selectionism during early development which controls the topology of a particular brain and enables restructuring in response to experience.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] They argue that memory is not a symbolic representation but a reflection of how the brain has changed its dynamics in order to achieve motor activity.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] This leads to a discussion of primary consciousness which integrates with perception into a means of directing immediate behavior and requires significant levels of reentrancy to achieve its effects.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] The problem of integrating, or *binding*, the activity of functionally segregated areas of the brain in order to concentrate attention on a particular activity in a short amount of time (typically 100-250 msecs) after the presentation of a stimulus is explored by means of large-scale simulations.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] It is shown that this can only happen if some elements interact more strongly among themselves than with the rest of the system including a large amount of reentrancy.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] These *functional clusters* are only slowly coming into the range of PET or fMRI scanning technology which commonly require much longer time scales.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] At any given time, only a small subset of the neuronal groups in the brain are contributing directly to consciousness and this cluster is called a *dynamic core*.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] It represents a single point of view and each different state of consciousness corresponds to a different subset.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Some dissociative disorders such as schizophrenia may result in the formation of multiple cores.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] One of the recurring issues in consciousness is the existence of *qualia*, such as redness, warmth and pain.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] It is not enough to identify each quale with a particular neuron or neuronal group; what is crucial is all the other groups which are highly influenced by the sensation and will fire at the same time.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Thus each conscious state deserves to be called a quale.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] A small perturbation of a group of neurons can affect the whole in a very short space of time provided the system is kept in a state of readiness by the thalamus.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Primary consciousness can build up a bodily based reference space even before language and higher-order consciousness appear.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] There is a preliminary approach to the relationship between conscious and unconscious processes, including sensors and motors, because so little is known.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] The evolution of language centres in the brain leads to higher order consciousness which enhances subjective experience and enables humans to describe qualia which are however experienced by a much wider range of animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] Thinking in humans has a range of representations—including pictorial.
[src:animal-consciousness/a-universe-of-consciousness] In contrast to computers which are Turing machines, brains are based on neuronal group selection.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-consciousness/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-consciousness/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The topic of animal consciousness is beset with a number of difficulties.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It poses the problem of other minds in an especially severe form because animals, lacking the ability to use human language, cannot communicate their experiences.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It is also difficult to reason objectively about the question because a denial that an animal is conscious is often taken to imply that they do not feel, their life has no value, and that harming them is not morally wrong.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, the 17th-century French philosopher René Descartes is sometimes criticised for enabling animal mistreatment through his animal machine view, which claimed that only humans are conscious.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Philosophers who consider subjective experience the essence of consciousness also generally believe, as a correlate, that the existence and nature of animal consciousness can never rigorously be known.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Other thinkers, such as the cognitive scientist Douglas Hofstadter, dismiss this argument as incoherent.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Animal consciousness has been actively researched for over one hundred years.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In 1927, the American functional psychologist Harvey Carr argued that any valid measure or understanding of awareness in animals depends on "an accurate and complete knowledge of its essential conditions in man".
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A more recent review concluded in 1985 that "the best approach is to use experiment (especially psychophysics) and observation to trace the dawning and ontogeny of self-consciousness, perception, communication, intention, beliefs, and reflection in normal human fetuses, infants, and children".
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In 2012, a group of neuroscientists signed the *Cambridge Declaration on Consciousness*, which "unequivocally" asserted that "humans are not unique in possessing the neurological substrates that generate consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Non-human animals, including all mammals and birds, and many other creatures, including octopuses, also possess these neural substrates." In 2024, more than 500 academics and scientists signed the *New York Declaration on Animal Consciousness*.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The declaration states that there is strong scientific support for consciousness in mammals and birds and that it is a realistic possibility in other vertebrates and many invertebrates.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It calls for these considerations to be taken into account in decisions affecting animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The mind–body problem in philosophy examines the relationship between mind and matter, and in particular the relationship between consciousness and the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A variety of approaches have been proposed.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Dualism maintains a rigid distinction between the realms of mind and matter.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Monism maintains that there is only one kind of stuff, and that mind and matter are both aspects of it.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The problem was addressed by pre-Aristotelian philosophers, and was famously addressed by René Descartes in the 17th century, resulting in Cartesian dualism.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Descartes believed that humans alone possess a non-physical mind, interpreting animal behaviour through a mechanistic model that denied animal consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The rejection of the mind–body dichotomy is found in French Structuralism, and is a position that generally characterized post-war French philosophy.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The absence of an empirically identifiable meeting point between the non-physical mind and its physical extension has proven problematic to dualism and many modern philosophers of mind maintain that the mind is not something separate from the body.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] These approaches have been particularly influential in the sciences, particularly in the fields of sociobiology, computer science, evolutionary psychology, and the neurosciences.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Epiphenomenalism is the theory in philosophy of mind that mental phenomena are caused by physical processes in the brain or that both are effects of a common cause, as opposed to mental phenomena driving the physical mechanics of the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The impression that thoughts, feelings, or sensations cause physical effects, is therefore to be understood as illusory to some extent.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, it is not the feeling of fear that produces an increase in heart beat, both are symptomatic of a common physiological origin, possibly in response to a legitimate external threat.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The history of epiphenomenalism goes back to the post-Cartesian attempt to solve the riddle of Cartesian dualism, i.e., of how mind and body could interact.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] La Mettrie, Leibniz and Spinoza all in their own way began this way of thinking.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The idea that even if the animal were conscious nothing would be added to the production of behavior, even in animals of the human type, was first voiced by La Mettrie (1745), and then by Cabanis (1802), and was further explicated by Hodgson (1870) and Huxley (1874).
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Huxley (1874) likened mental phenomena to the whistle on a steam locomotive.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, epiphenomenalism flourished primarily as it found a niche among methodological or scientific behaviorism.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In the early 1900s scientific behaviorists such as Ivan Pavlov, John B.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Skinner began the attempt to uncover laws describing the relationship between stimuli and responses, without reference to inner mental phenomena.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Instead of adopting a form of eliminativism or mental fictionalism, positions that deny that inner mental phenomena exist, a behaviorist was able to adopt epiphenomenalism in order to allow for the existence of mind.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, by the 1960s, scientific behaviourism met substantial difficulties and eventually gave way to the cognitive revolution.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Participants in that revolution, such as Jerry Fodor, reject epiphenomenalism and insist upon the efficacy of the mind.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Fodor even speaks of "epiphobia"—fear that one is becoming an epiphenomenalist.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Karl Popper develops in the book *The Self and Its Brain* a similar evolutionary argument.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In his interactions with scientists and other veterinarians, Rollin asserts that he was regularly asked to prove animals are conscious and provide scientifically acceptable grounds for claiming they feel pain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The denial of animal consciousness by scientists has been labelled as mentophobia by Donald Griffin.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Academic reviews of the topic are equivocal, noting that the argument that animals have at least simple conscious thoughts and feelings has strong support, but some critics continue to question how reliably animal mental states can be determined.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A refereed journal *Animal Sentience* launched in 2016 by the Institute of Science and Policy of The Humane Society of the United States is devoted to research on this and related topics.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness is an elusive concept that presents many difficulties when attempts are made to define it.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Its study has progressively become an interdisciplinary challenge for numerous researchers, including ethologists, neurologists, cognitive neuroscientists, philosophers, psychologists and psychiatrists.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In 1976, Richard Dawkins wrote, "The evolution of the capacity to simulate seems to have culminated in subjective consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Why this should have happened is, to me, the most profound mystery facing modern biology." In 2004, eight neuroscientists felt it was still too soon for a definition.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] We have no idea how consciousness emerges from the physical activity of the brain and we do not know whether consciousness can emerge from non-biological systems, such as computers...
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] At this point the reader will expect to find a careful and precise definition of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness has not yet become a scientific term that can be defined in this way.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] in many different and often ambiguous ways.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Precise definitions of different aspects of consciousness will emerge ... but to make precise definitions at this stage is premature.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness is sometimes defined as the quality or state of being aware of an external object or something within oneself.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It has been defined somewhat vaguely as: subjectivity, awareness, sentience, the ability to experience or to feel, wakefulness, having a sense of selfhood, and the executive control system of the mind.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Despite the difficulty in definition, many philosophers believe that there is a broadly shared underlying intuition about what consciousness is.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Sentience (the ability to feel, perceive, or to experience subjectivity) is not the same as self-awareness (being aware of oneself as an individual).
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The mirror test is sometimes considered to be an operational test for self-awareness, and the handful of animals that have passed it are often considered to be self-aware.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It remains debatable whether recognition of one's mirror image can be properly construed to imply full self-awareness, particularly given that robots are being constructed which appear to pass the test.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, this view has been criticized because consciousness has yet to be shown to be a process, and the so-called "hard problem" of relating consciousness directly to brain activity remains elusive.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Since Descartes's proposal of dualism, it became general consensus that the mind had become a matter of philosophy and that science was not able to penetrate the issue of consciousness – that consciousness was outside of space and time.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, in recent decades many scholars have begun to move toward a science of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Antonio Damasio and Gerald Edelman are two neuroscientists who have led the move to neural correlates of the self and of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Damasio has demonstrated that emotions and their biological foundation play a critical role in high level cognition, and Edelman has created a framework for analyzing consciousness through a scientific outlook.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The current problem consciousness researchers face involves explaining how and why consciousness arises from neural computation.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In his research on this problem, Edelman has developed a theory of consciousness, in which he has coined the terms primary consciousness and secondary consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Eugene Linden, author of *The Parrot's Lament* suggests there are many examples of animal behavior and intelligence that surpass what people would suppose to be the boundary of animal consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Linden contends that in many of these documented examples, a variety of animal species exhibit behavior that can only be attributed to emotion, and to a level of consciousness that we would normally ascribe only to our own species.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness in mammals (including humans) is an aspect of the mind generally thought to comprise qualities such as subjectivity, sentience, and the ability to perceive the relationship between oneself and one's environment.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It is a subject of much research in philosophy of mind, psychology, neuroscience, and cognitive science.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some philosophers divide consciousness into phenomenal consciousness, which is subjective experience itself, and access consciousness, which refers to the global availability of information to processing systems in the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Phenomenal consciousness has many different experienced qualities, often referred to as qualia.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Phenomenal consciousness is usually consciousness *of* something or *about* something, a property known as intentionality in philosophy of mind.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In humans, there are three common methods of studying consciousness: verbal reporting, behavioural demonstrations, and neural correlation with conscious activity, though these can only be generalized to non-human taxa with varying degrees of difficulty.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In a new study conducted in rhesus monkeys, Ben-Haim and his team used a process dissociation approach that predicted opposite behavioral outcomes for the two modes of perception.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] They found that monkeys displayed exactly the same opposite behavioral outcomes as humans when they were aware or unaware of the stimuli presented.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The sense in which animals (or human infants) can be said to have consciousness or a self-concept has been hotly debated; it is often referred to as the debate over animal minds.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The best known research technique in this area is the mirror test devised by Gordon G.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Gallup, in which the skin of an animal (or human infant) is marked, while they are asleep or sedated, with a mark that cannot be seen directly but is visible in a mirror.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The animals are then allowed to see their reflection in a mirror; if the animal spontaneously directs grooming behaviour towards the mark, that is taken as an indication that they are aware of themselves.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Over the past 30 years, many studies have found evidence that animals recognise themselves in mirrors.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Until recently, it was thought that self-recognition was absent in animals without a neocortex, and was restricted to mammals with large brains and well-developed social cognition.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, in 2008, a study of self-recognition in corvids reported significant results for magpies.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Mammals and birds inherited the same brain components from their last common ancestor nearly 300 million years ago, and have since independently evolved and formed significantly different brain types.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The results of the mirror and mark tests showed that neocortex-less magpies are capable of understanding that a mirror image belongs to their own body.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The findings show that magpies respond in the mirror and mark tests in a manner similar to apes, dolphins and elephants.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The magpies were chosen to study based on their empathy and lifestyle, a possible precursor to their ability to develop self-awareness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For chimpanzees, the occurrence is about 75% in young adults and considerably less in young and old individuals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For monkeys, non-primate mammals, and a number of bird species, exploration of the mirror and social displays were observed.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Hints at mirror-induced self-directed behavior have been obtained.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] According to a 2019 study, cleaner wrasses have become the first fish ever observed to pass the mirror test.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, the test's inventor Gordon Gallup has said that the fish were most likely trying to scrape off a perceived parasite on another fish and that they did not demonstrate self-recognition.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The authors of the study responded that because the fish checked themselves in the mirror before and after the scraping, this meant that the fish had self-awareness and recognized that their reflections belonged to their own bodies.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The mirror test has attracted controversy among some researchers because it is entirely focused on vision, the primary sense in humans, while other species rely more heavily on other senses such as the olfactory sense in dogs.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A study in 2015 showed that the "sniff test of self-recognition (STSR)" provides evidence of self-awareness in dogs.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Another approach to determine whether a non-human animal is conscious derives from passive speech research with a macaw (see Arielle).
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers propose that by passively listening to an animal's voluntary speech, it is possible to learn about the thoughts of another creature and to determine that the speaker is conscious.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] This type of research was originally used to investigate a child's crib speech by Weir (1962) and in investigations of early speech in children by Greenfield and others (1976).
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Zipf's law might be able to be used to indicate if a given dataset of animal communication indicate an intelligent natural language.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers have used this algorithm to study bottlenose dolphin language.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Further arguments revolve around the ability of animals to feel pain or suffering, which implies consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] If animals can be shown to suffer in ways comparable to humans, ethical arguments against human suffering may be extended to animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some scholars argue that pain can be inferred from non-purposeful or maladaptive reactions to negative stimuli.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] One such reaction is transmarginal inhibition, a phenomenon observed in both humans and some animals that resembles mental breakdown.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Cosmologist Carl Sagan argues that humans often deny animal suffering to justify practices such as enslavement, experimentation, and consumption.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] He contends that behavioral similarities between humans and other animals challenge such denials.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] John Webster, professor of animal husbandry, argues that suffering is not dependent on intelligence or brain size.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] He states that sentient animals actively seek pleasure and display behaviors indicating enjoyment, such as basking in the sun.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, there is no consensus about which organisms are capable of experiencing pain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Philosopher Justin Leiber discusses varying views: Michel de Montaigne attributes consciousness to insects and even plants, while Peter Singer and Samuel Clarke deny it in simpler organisms like sponges.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Singer places the boundary somewhere between shrimp and oysters, while others speculate about insects, spiders, or tapeworms.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some critics draw comparisons to plants, questioning whether a focus on animal suffering is entirely distinct.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Science writer Carol Kaesuk Yoon describes how plants, when damaged, initiate chemical defenses and repair processes, though these do not necessarily imply consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Cognitive bias in animals is a pattern of deviation in judgment, whereby inferences about other animals and situations may be drawn in an illogical fashion.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Individuals create their own "subjective social reality" from their perception of the input.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It refers to the question "Is the glass half empty or half full?", used as an indicator of optimism or pessimism.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Cognitive biases have been shown in a wide range of species including rats, dogs, rhesus macaques, sheep, chicks, starlings and honeybees.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux advocates avoiding terms derived from human subjective experience when discussing brain functions in animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, the common practice of calling brain circuits that detect and respond to threats "fear circuits" implies that these circuits are responsible for feelings of fear.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] LeDoux argues that Pavlovian fear conditioning should be renamed Pavlovian threat conditioning to avoid the implication that "fear" is being acquired in rats or humans.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Key to his theoretical change is the notion of survival functions mediated by survival circuits, the purpose of which is to keep organisms alive rather than to make emotions.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, defensive survival circuits exist to detect and respond to threats.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] While all organisms can do this, only organisms that can be conscious of their own brain's activities can feel fear.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Fear is a conscious experience and occurs the same way as any other kind of conscious experience: via cortical circuits that allow attention to certain forms of brain activity.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] LeDoux argues the only differences between an emotional and non-emotion state of consciousness are the underlying neural ingredients that contribute to the state.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Neuroscience is the scientific study of the nervous system.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It is a highly active interdisciplinary science that collaborates with many other fields.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The scope of neuroscience has broadened recently to include molecular, cellular, developmental, structural, functional, evolutionary, computational, and medical aspects of the nervous system.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Theoretical studies of neural networks are being complemented with techniques for imaging sensory and motor tasks in the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] According to a 2008 paper, neuroscience explanations of psychological phenomena currently have a "seductive allure", and "seem to generate more public interest" than explanations which do not contain neuroscientific information.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] They found that subjects who were not neuroscience experts "judged that explanations with logically irrelevant neuroscience information were more satisfying than explanations without.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The neural correlates of consciousness constitute the minimal set of neuronal events and mechanisms sufficient for a specific conscious percept.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Neuroscientists use empirical approaches to discover neural correlates of subjective phenomena.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The set should be *minimal* because, if the brain is sufficient to give rise to any given conscious experience, the question is which of its components is necessary to produce it.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Visual sense and representation was reviewed in 1998 by Francis Crick and Christof Koch.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] They concluded sensory neuroscience can be used as a bottom-up approach to studying consciousness, and suggested experiments to test various hypotheses in this research stream.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A feature that distinguishes humans from most animals is that we are not born with an extensive repertoire of behavioral programs that would enable us to survive on our own ("physiological prematurity").
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] To compensate for this, we have an unmatched ability to learn, i.e., to consciously acquire such programs by imitation or exploration.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Once consciously acquired and sufficiently exercised, these programs can become automated to the extent that their execution happens beyond the realms of our awareness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Take, as an example, the incredible fine motor skills exerted in playing a Beethoven piano sonata or the sensorimotor coordination required to ride a motorcycle along a curvy mountain road.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Such complex behaviors are possible only because a sufficient number of the subprograms involved can be executed with minimal or even suspended conscious control.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In fact, the conscious system may actually interfere somewhat with these automated programs.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The growing ability of neuroscientists to manipulate neurons using methods from molecular biology in combination with optical tools depends on the simultaneous development of appropriate behavioural assays and model organisms amenable to large-scale genomic analysis and manipulation.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A combination of such fine-grained neuronal analysis in animals with ever more sensitive psychophysical and brain imaging techniques in humans, complemented by the development of a robust theoretical predictive framework, will hopefully lead to a rational understanding of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is a part of the brain of mammals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It consists of the grey matter, or neuronal cell bodies and unmyelinated fibers, surrounding the deeper white matter (myelinated axons) in the cerebrum.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is smooth in rodents and other small mammals, whereas in primates and other larger mammals it has deep grooves and wrinkles.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] These folds increase the surface area of the neocortex considerably without taking up too much more volume.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Also, neurons within the same wrinkle have more opportunity for connectivity, while neurons in different wrinkles have less opportunity for connectivity, leading to compartmentalization of the cortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is divided into frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal lobes, which perform different functions.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, the occipital lobe contains the primary visual cortex, and the temporal lobe contains the primary auditory cortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Further subdivisions or areas of neocortex are responsible for more specific cognitive processes.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The neocortex is the newest part of the cerebral cortex to evolve (hence the prefix "neo"); the other parts of the cerebral cortex are the paleocortex and archicortex, collectively known as the allocortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In humans, 90% of the cerebral cortex is neocortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Researchers have argued that consciousness in mammals arises in the neocortex, and therefore by extension used to argue that consciousness cannot arise in animals which lack a neocortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For instance, evidence suggests the pallium in bird brains to be functionally equivalent to the mammalian cerebral cortex as a basis of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Attention is the cognitive process of selectively concentrating on one aspect of the environment while ignoring other things.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Attention has also been referred to as the allocation of processing resources.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Attention also has variations amongst cultures.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Voluntary attention develops in specific cultural and institutional contexts through engagement in cultural activities with more competent community members.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Most experiments show that one neural correlate of attention is enhanced firing.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] If a neuron has a certain response to a stimulus when the animal is not attending to the stimulus, then when the animal does attend to the stimulus, the neuron's response will be enhanced even if the physical characteristics of the stimulus remain the same.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In many cases attention produces changes in the EEG.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Many animals, including humans, produce gamma waves (40–60 Hz) when focusing attention on a particular object or activity.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Extended consciousness is an animal's autobiographical self-perception.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It is thought to arise in the brains of animals which have a substantial capacity for memory and reason.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It does not necessarily require language.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The perception of a historic and future self arises from a stream of information from the immediate environment and from neural structures related to memory.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The concept was popularised by Antonio Damasio and is used in biological psychology.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Extended consciousness is said to arise in structures in the human brain described as *image spaces* and *dispositional spaces*.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Image spaces imply areas where sensory impressions of all types are processed, including the focused awareness of the core consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Dispositional spaces include convergence zones, which are networks in the brain where memories are processed and recalled, and where knowledge is merged with immediate experience.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Metacognition is defined as "cognition about cognition", or "knowing about knowing." It can take many forms; it includes knowledge about when and how to use particular strategies for learning or for problem solving.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It has been suggested that metacognition in some animals provides evidence for cognitive self-awareness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] There are generally two components of metacognition: knowledge about cognition, and regulation of cognition.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Writings on metacognition can be traced back at least as far as *De Anima* and the *Parva Naturalia* of the Greek philosopher Aristotle.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Metacognologists believe that the ability to consciously think about thinking is unique to sapient species and indeed is one of the definitions of sapience.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] There is evidence that rhesus monkeys and apes can make accurate judgments about the strengths of their memories of fact and monitor their own uncertainty, while attempts to demonstrate metacognition in birds have been inconclusive.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A 2007 study provided some evidence for metacognition in rats, but further analysis suggested that they may have been following simple operant conditioning principles, or a behavioral economic model.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Mirror neurons are neurons that fire both when an animal acts and when the animal observes the same action performed by another.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Thus, the neuron "mirrors" the behavior of the other, as though the observer were themselves acting.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Such neurons have been directly observed in primate and other species including birds.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The function of the mirror system is a subject of much speculation.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Many researchers in cognitive neuroscience and cognitive psychology consider that this system provides the physiological mechanism for the perception action coupling (see the common coding theory).
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] They argue that mirror neurons may be important for understanding the actions of other people, and for learning new skills by imitation.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers also speculate that mirror systems may simulate observed actions, and thus contribute to theory of mind skills, while others relate mirror neurons to language abilities.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Neuroscientists such as Marco Iacoboni (UCLA) have argued that mirror neuron systems in the human brain help us understand the actions and intentions of other people.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In a study published in March 2005, Iacoboni and his colleagues reported that mirror neurons could discern if another person who was picking up a cup of tea planned to drink from it or clear it from the table.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In addition, Iacoboni and a number of other researchers have argued that mirror neurons are the neural basis of the human capacity for emotions such as empathy.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Ramachandran has speculated that mirror neurons may provide the neurological basis of self-awareness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Consciousness is likely an evolved adaptation since it meets George Williams' criteria of species universality, complexity, and functionality, and it is a trait that apparently increases fitness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Opinions are divided as to where in biological evolution consciousness emerged and about whether or not consciousness has survival value.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It has been argued that consciousness emerged (i) exclusively with the first humans, (ii) exclusively with the first mammals, (iii) independently in mammals and birds, or (iv) with the first reptiles.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Donald Griffin suggests in his book *Animal Minds* a gradual evolution of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Each of these scenarios raises the question of the possible survival value of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In his paper "Evolution of consciousness," John Eccles argues that special anatomical and physical adaptations of the mammalian cerebral cortex gave rise to consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Once in place, this recursive circuitry may well have provided a basis for the subsequent development of many of the functions that consciousness facilitates in higher organisms, as outlined by Bernard J.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Richard Dawkins suggested that humans evolved consciousness in order to make themselves the subjects of thought.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Daniel Povinelli suggests that large, tree-climbing apes evolved consciousness to take into account one's own mass when moving safely among tree branches.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Consistent with this hypothesis, Gordon Gallup found that chimpanzees and orangutans, but not little monkeys or terrestrial gorillas, demonstrated self-awareness in mirror tests.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The concept of consciousness can refer to voluntary action, awareness, or wakefulness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] However, even voluntary behaviour involves unconscious mechanisms.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Many cognitive processes take place in the cognitive unconscious, unavailable to conscious awareness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some behaviours are conscious when learned but then become unconscious, seemingly automatic.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Learning, especially implicitly learning a skill, can take place outside of consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For example, plenty of people know how to turn right when they ride a bike, but very few can accurately explain how they actually do so.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Neural Darwinism is a large scale theory of brain function initially proposed in 1978 by the American biologist Gerald Edelman.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Primary consciousness can be defined as simple awareness that includes perception and emotion.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] As such, it is ascribed to most animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] By contrast, secondary consciousness depends on and includes such features as self-reflective awareness, abstract thinking, volition and metacognition.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Edelman's theory focuses on two nervous system organizations: the brainstem and limbic systems on one side and the thalamus and cerebral cortex on the other side.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The brain stem and limbic system take care of essential body functioning and survival, while the thalamocortical system receives signals from sensory receptors and sends out signals to voluntary muscles such as those of the arms and legs.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The theory asserts that the connection of these two systems during evolution helped animals learn adaptive behaviors.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Other scientists have argued against Edelman's theory, instead suggesting that primary consciousness might have emerged with the basic vegetative systems of the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] This is based on neurological data showing the thalamic, hippocampal, orbitofrontal, insula, and midbrain sites are the key to consciousness of thirst.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] These scientists also point out that the cortex might not be as important to primary consciousness as some neuroscientists have believed.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Some researchers argue that systematic disruption of cortical regions in nonhuman animals does not prevent consciousness, and that reports of consciousness in children born without a cortex are consistent with this view.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] On this account, brainstem mechanisms are proposed to play a primary role in consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Still, these scientists concede that higher order consciousness does involve the cortex and complex communication between different areas of the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] While animals with primary consciousness have long-term memory, they lack explicit narrative, and, at best, can only deal with the immediate scene in the remembered present.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] While they still have an advantage over animals lacking such ability, evolution has brought forth a growing complexity in consciousness, particularly in mammals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Animals with this complexity are said to have secondary consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Secondary consciousness is seen in animals with semantic capabilities, such as the four great apes.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] It is present in its richest form in the human species, which is unique in possessing complex language made up of syntax and semantics.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The ability of an animal to relate a present complex scene to their own previous history of learning conferred an adaptive evolutionary advantage.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] At much later evolutionary epochs, further re-entrant circuits appeared that linked semantic and linguistic performance to categorical and conceptual memory systems.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] This development enabled the emergence of secondary consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Ursula Voss of the Universität Bonn believes that the theory of protoconsciousness may serve as adequate explanation for self-recognition found in birds, as they would develop secondary consciousness during REM sleep.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] She added that many types of birds have very sophisticated language systems.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Don Kuiken of the University of Alberta finds such research interesting as well as if we continue to study consciousness with animal models (with differing types of consciousness), we would be able to separate the different forms of reflectiveness found in today's world.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] For the advocates of the idea of a secondary consciousness, self-recognition serves as a critical component and a key defining measure.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] What is most interesting then, is the evolutionary appeal that arises with the concept of self-recognition.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] In non-human species and in children, the mirror test (see above) has been used as an indicator of self-awareness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] A 2020 paper by Jonathan Birch, Alexandra K.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] Clayton outlined a multidimensional approach to animal consciousness, intended to account for variation in conscious experience across species.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The authors propose that consciousness may not be meaningfully represented along a single continuum, and instead suggest five distinct dimensions for constructing species-specific profiles.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p01] The authors suggest that this framework could facilitate comparative studies of consciousness in different taxa, including mammals, birds, and cephalopods.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] In 2012, a group of neuroscientists attending a conference on "Consciousness in Human and non-Human Animals" at the University of Cambridge in the UK, signed the *Cambridge Declaration on Consciousness* (see box on the right).
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] In 2024, a conference on "The Emerging Science of Animal Consciousness" at New York University produced *The New York Declaration on Animal Consciousness*.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] A common image is the *scala naturae*, the ladder of nature on which animals of different species occupy successively higher rungs, with humans typically at the top.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] A more useful approach has been to recognize that different animals may have different kinds of cognitive processes, which are better understood in terms of the ways in which they are cognitively adapted to their different ecological niches, than by positing any kind of hierarchy.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Dogs were previously listed as non-self-aware animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Traditionally, self-consciousness was evaluated via the mirror test.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] But dogs, and many other animals, are not (as) visually oriented.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The study further suggests adopting a species-specific, rather than anthropocentric, approach to research on animal consciousness.This study has been confirmed by another study.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Research with captive grey parrots, especially Irene Pepperberg's work with an individual named Alex, has demonstrated they possess the ability to associate simple human words with meanings, and to intelligently apply the abstract concepts of shape, colour, number, zero-sense, etc.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] According to Pepperberg and other scientists, they perform many cognitive tasks at the level of dolphins, chimpanzees, and even human toddlers.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Another notable African grey is N'kisi, which in 2004 was said to have a vocabulary of over 950 words which she used in creative ways.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] For example, when Jane Goodall visited N'kisi in his New York home, he greeted her with "Got a chimp?" because he had seen pictures of her with chimpanzees in Africa.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] In 2011, research led by Dalila Bovet of Paris West University Nanterre La Défense, demonstrated grey parrots were able to coordinate and collaborate with each other to an extent.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] They were able to solve problems such as two birds having to pull strings at the same time to obtain food.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] In another example, one bird stood on a perch to release a food-laden tray, while the other pulled the tray out from the test apparatus.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The birds were observed waiting for their partners to perform the necessary actions so their behaviour could be synchronized.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The parrots appeared to express individual preferences as to which of the other test birds they would work with.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] It was thought that self-recognition was restricted to mammals with large brains and highly evolved social cognition, but absent from animals without a neocortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] However, in 2008, an investigation of self-recognition in corvids was conducted to determine the ability of self-recognition in the magpie.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The results of the mirror test showed that although magpies do not have a neocortex, they are capable of understanding that a mirror image belongs to their own body.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The findings show that magpies respond to the mirror test in a manner similar to that of apes, dolphins, killer whales, pigs and elephants.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] A 2020 study found that carrion crows show a neuronal response that correlates with their perception of a stimulus, which they argue to be an empirical marker of (avian) sensory consciousness – the conscious perception of sensory input – in the crows which do not have a cerebral cortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The study thereby substantiates the theory that conscious perception does not require a cerebral cortex and that the basic foundations for it – and possibly for human-type consciousness – may have evolved before the last common ancestor >320 Mya or independently in birds.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] A related study showed that the birds' pallium's neuroarchitecture is reminiscent of the mammalian cortex.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] A 2025 review applied a five-dimensional framework of consciousness to corvids, examining sensory, evaluative, temporal, and self-related aspects of their experience.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Drawing on behavioural and neurological evidence, the authors argue that corvids exhibit sophisticated cognitive capacities across all dimensions, including high perceptual acuity, emotional evaluation, episodic-like memory, future planning, and possible forms of self-awareness and theory of mind.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] While not claiming definitive proof of consciousness, the review supports the growing consensus that corvids are plausible sentient beings and proposes they serve as a model group for the comparative study of non-mammalian consciousness.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Octopuses are highly intelligent, possibly more so than any other order of invertebrates.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] The level of their intelligence and learning capability are debated, but maze and problem-solving studies show they have both short- and long-term memory.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Octopus have a highly complex nervous system, only part of which is localized in their brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Two-thirds of an octopus's neurons are found in the nerve cords of their arms.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Octopus arms show a variety of complex reflex actions that persist even when they have no input from the brain.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Unlike vertebrates, the complex motor skills of octopuses are not organized in their brain using an internal somatotopic map of their body, instead using a non-somatotopic system unique to large-brained invertebrates.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Some octopuses, such as the mimic octopus, move their arms in ways that emulate the shape and movements of other sea creatures.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] In laboratory studies, octopuses can easily be trained to distinguish between different shapes and patterns.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] They reportedly use observational learning, although the validity of these findings is contested.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Octopuses have also been observed to play: repeatedly releasing bottles or toys into a circular current in their aquariums and then catching them.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Octopuses often escape from their aquarium and sometimes enter others.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] They have boarded fishing boats and opened holds to eat crabs.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] At least four specimens of the veined octopus (*Amphioctopus marginatus*) have been witnessed retrieving discarded coconut shells, manipulating them, and then reassembling them to use as shelter.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] Shamanistic and other traditional cultures and folk tales speak of animal spirits and the consciousness of animals.
[src:animal-consciousness/animal-consciousness-p02] In India, Jains consider all the jivas (living organisms, including plants, animals and insects) to be conscious.
